x4freetext: Reaction mechanisms and shell structure effects in
Fe-54+Li-6 and Ni-58+d reactions
targets were made of natural Ni foils ranging in
thickness from 2.3 To 2.42 mg/cm2 and with a purity of
99.4%. The error of the thickness was about 3%.
enriched Ni-58 (99.89%) Was electroplated onto gold
(8.73 - 9.64 mg/cm2, +-3%) backing. The thicknesses of
Ni-58 targets were 4.22 - 6.74 mg/cm2, +-5%.
enriched Fe-54 (97.4%) Was electroplating onto gold
(11.65 - 12.28 mg/cm2) backing. The thicknesses of
Fe-54 targets were 3.02 - 3.67 mg/cm2, +-5%.
the stacked foil technique was used to measure the
excitation functions and mean recoil ranges. Nine
stacks were prepared. Most stacks contained 12 pairs of
target and catcher foils. The catcher foils were
aluminum (purity 99.5%) With thickness of around 2
mg/cm2 in the first two low energy irradiations.
to eliminate the interference from the iron in the Al
foils increased purity (99.98%) were used at higher
bombarding energies (thickness: 2.93 - 3.61 mg/cm2).
Al foils were used for energy degradation.
the beam energy was determined by magnetic analysis or
based on particle ranges in aluminum. Water-cooled
target holder served as Faraday-cup. The integrated
charge was about 2 micri-ampere-hour. The longest
irradiation time was 16.0 Hours. The particle energy
in each foil was calculated according to
C.F. Williamson et al., Rapport CEA-R-3042 (1966).
the uncertainty of the energy scale contains the
uncertainty of the initial beam energy and the
uncertainty resulted by the degradation process, which
may Be as large as 2 MeV or 4 MeV for the last foils
in the deuteron and lithium ion runs, respectively.
the errors reflect the uncertainties, but are not given
-target thickness                    3-5%
-backing thickness                     3%
-detector efficiency  Ge(Li)        8-10%
NaI(Tl)           5%
proportional counters       3%
-detector geometry                   2-5%
-chemical yields                       5%
data were taken from table 5 and  6 of Nucl.
